          <h2 class="details-title">Raigad Fort: The Capital of the Maratha Empire</h2>
          <p>
            Perched atop the Sahyadri hills in Maharashtra’s Raigad district, Raigad Fort is a monument of immense
            historical and cultural significance. Once the capital of the Maratha Empire under Chhatrapati Shivaji
            Maharaj, this majestic fort is a testament to his vision, bravery, and administrative genius. Known as the
            "Gibraltar of the East", Raigad Fort stands as a symbol of Maratha pride and resilience.</p>
          <h5>Historical Significance</h5>
          <ul>
            <li>Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj’s Coronation: In 1674, Shivaji was crowned as the first Chhatrapati of the
              Maratha Empire at Raigad Fort, marking the beginning of Swarajya (self-rule).</li>
            <li>Strategic Location: Located 2,700 feet above sea level, the fort was nearly impregnable and served as
              the base for military operations and administration.</li>
            <li>Architectural and Cultural Hub: The fort housed royal palaces, a court, granaries, and temples, making
              it the heart of Maratha governance.
            </li>
          </ul>
          <h5>Architectural Marvels of Raigad Fort</h5>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <strong>The Maha Darwaza (Main Gate)</strong>
              <p>A massive entrance that reflects the fort's architectural brilliance. It served as a protective barrier
                against invaders.</p>
                <img style="max-width: 100%; max-height: 400px;" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/de/Nagarkhana%2C_Raigad_Fort%2C_India.jpg/640px-Nagarkhana%2C_Raigad_Fort%2C_India.jpg" alt="">
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>The Royal Palace</strong>
              <p>The ruins of Shivaji’s palace, made primarily of wood, showcase the grandeur of Maratha architecture.
              </p>
              <img style="max-width: 100%; max-height: 400px;" src="https://www.tripnight.com/public/thumbs/monuments/7294/ENBnjlmiqt3W_468_738.jpg" alt="">
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>The Jagdishwar Temple</strong>
              <p>Dedicated to Lord Shiva, this temple reflects Shivaji Maharaj's devotion and spiritual beliefs.</p>
              <img style="max-width: 100%; max-height: 400px;" src="https://www.tripnight.com/public/thumbs/monuments/7275/lew07bQLuJFH_468_738.jpg" alt="">
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>The Samadhi of Shivaji Maharaj</strong>
              <p>A simple yet profound memorial marks the site of the Maratha king's final resting place. Nearby lies
                the samadhi of his loyal dog, Waghya, symbolizing loyalty and companionship.</p>
                <img style="max-width: 100%; max-height: 400px;" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Chhatrapati_Shivaji_Maharaj_Samadhi_Raigad.jpg/640px-Chhatrapati_Shivaji_Maharaj_Samadhi_Raigad.jpg" alt="">
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Hirakani Buruj (Bastion)</strong>
              <p>This bastion is named after a brave woman, Hirakani, who climbed down the steep fort walls to reach her
                infant.</p>
                <img style="max-width: 100%; max-height: 400px;" src="https://content.jdmagicbox.com/comp/raigad-maharashtra/j8/9999p2141.2141.220829231054.b9j8/catalogue/hirkani-buruj-raigad-maharashtra-EFlc5GpJLb-250.jpg" alt="">
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Takmak Tok</strong>
              <p>A cliff used for executing prisoners, this site offers breathtaking views of the surrounding valley.
              </p>
              <img style="max-width: 100%; max-height: 400px;" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1f/Takmak_Tok%2C_Raigad_Fort_in_Raigad%2C_India.jpg/1200px-Takmak_Tok%2C_Raigad_Fort_in_Raigad%2C_India.jpg" alt="">
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Market Area</strong>
              <p>The remnants of the ancient market where goods were displayed on stone platforms showcase the fort’s
                self-sustaining nature.</p>
                <img style="max-width: 100%; max-height: 400px;" src="https://files.yappe.in/place/full/marketplace-of-raigad-6353126.webp" alt="">
            </li>
          </ol>
          <h5>Trekking to Raigad Fort</h5>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <strong>Base Village</strong>
              <p>Pachad village is the starting point for most trekkers.</p>
              <img style="max-width: 100%; max-height: 400px;" src="" alt="">
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Climbing the Steps</strong>
              <p>The fort is accessible via 1,737 stone steps, offering a challenging yet rewarding trek.</p>
              <img style="max-width: 100%; max-height: 400px;" src="" alt="">
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Ropeway</strong>
              <p>For those unable to trek, a ropeway ride provides a quick and scenic ascent to the fort. </p>
              <img style="max-width: 100%; max-height: 400px;" src="" alt="">
            </li>
          </ol>
          <h5>Best Time to Visit</h5>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Winter (November to February)</strong>: The pleasant weather makes trekking enjoyable.</li>
            <li><strong>Monsoon (June to September)</strong>: The lush greenery and cascading waterfalls enhance the beauty, though trekking can be slippery.</li>
            <li><strong>Summer (March to May)</strong>: Visit early mornings or evenings to avoid the heat.</li>
          </ul>
          <h5>Travel Tips</h5>
          <ul>
            <li>Wear sturdy trekking shoes and carry sufficient water.</li>
            <li>Hire a local guide to understand the historical and architectural significance of the fort.</li>
            <li>Avoid visiting during peak summer afternoons due to the heat.</li>
